<div class="row">
<div align="center" class="col-xs-12">
<h4><b>3. Tropical and Sidereal Zodiac</b></h4>
</div><!--/.col-xs-12 -->
<div class="mtop15p">
Tropical and Sidereal Zodiac are astrological terms used to describe two different definitions of a year.
</div>
</div><!--/.row -->
<div class="row">
<div class="col-xs-6">
 <div><h5><b>Tropical Zodiac (Sayana System)</b></h5></div>
 <div>
  Sayana meaning Moving. They consider Sun is the center and other are moving around it (Helio-centric Theory).
  Therefore, Zodiac is moving.<br/>
  Western Astrologers considers Tropical Zodiac.
 </div>
</div><!--/.col-xs-6 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
<div class="row">
<div class="col-xs-6">
 <div><h5><b>Sidereal Zodiac (Niryana System)</b></h5></div>
 <div>
  Niryana meaning Fixed. They consider Earth is the center (Viewing from the Earth) and other are moving around 
  it (Geo-centric Theory). Therefore, Zodiac is fixed.<br/>
  Vedic Astrologers considers Tropical Zodiac.
 </div>
</div><!--/.col-xs-6 -->
</div><!--/.row -->
<div class="row">
<div class="col-xs-6">
<!-- -->
<div class="list-group">
<div class="list-group-item">
 <div align="center"><h5><b>Ayanamsa</b></h5></div>
 <div>
 As the <code data-toggle="tooltip" title="The change in the orientation of the rotational axis of Earth is called as Earth's Precession">Earth's Precession</code> 
 changes every year, the difference between the tropical zodiac and the sidereal zodiac changes.
 This difference is called <i>Ayanamsa</i> (Sidereal difference).<br/>
 &emsp;There are many opinions on the correct value of Ayanamsa because nobody knows exactly which star should be 
 considered as the starting point of the zodiac.<br/><br/>
 &emsp;We will use Chitrapaksha/Lahiri Ayanamsa which is accepted by most Vedic astrologers of India.
 </div>
 <!-- -->
 </div><!--/.list-group -->
 </div><!--/.list-group-item -->
</div><!--/.col-xs-6 -->
</div><!--/.row -->